<section id="faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="sec-head"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2></div>
    <div class="faq-grid">
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>Which coding agents does Robium work with?</h3>
        <p>
          Claude Code today — <code>npx robium-ai install</code> sets it up in
          one command. Cursor and Gemini are next: the skills are plain
          Markdown, and the per-agent manifest is the only missing piece.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>Do I need a robot or a GPU?</h3>
        <p>
          No. Every reference app runs in simulation on a laptop — manip-trial
          trains and evaluates a policy on a GPU-less MacBook, and nav-trial
          runs Gazebo fully headless in Docker.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>What exactly is a skill?</h3>
        <p>
          A hand-crafted, versioned Markdown package of expertise your agent
          loads when a task calls for it — not just how-to, but judgment: which
          simulator, which viewer, which data source, and the failure modes
          docs don't mention.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>How do skills stay correct as the ecosystem moves?</h3>
        <p>
          Every skill is versioned, hardened by building the reference apps,
          and updated when APIs move — LeRobot's churn forced our own 2.0.0
          bump. A dedicated skill folds each session's learnings back into the
          catalog.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>Is it free?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes — MIT-licensed, everything public at
          <a href="https://github.com/robium-ai">github.com/robium-ai</a>: the
          plugin, the reference apps, the CLI, and this site.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="qa">
        <h3>Can I contribute a skill?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes, and the contribution unit is deliberately small: one skill. Copy
          the template, pass the validator, open a PR.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

